bib_record.title: Gamma-Ray Production and Inferred Inelastic Neutron Cross Sections for Nickel Isotopes

free_txt: Preliminary results.
Data corrected for
- dead time
- small dc current in beam
- neutron attenuation
- gamma attenuation
- neutron multiple scattering
- non parallel neutron flux
- angular variation of n-source
40 cubic centimeter GeLi detector calibrated
with standard sources.
Long counter for neutron flux normalization
proton recoil detector for neutron flux normalization.
Typical uncertainties in data are
detector efficiency, +- 6 percent
finite sample correction, +- 4 percent
calculated conversion factors, +- 2 percent
The T(p,n)3He reaction provided neutron bursts
in this pulsed beam experiment. The neutron energy
spread was due both to target thickness effects on
the protons and the effect of reaction kinematics
caused by the sample's subtended solid angle. The two
effects summed in quadrature gave an estimated
neutron energy spread of ~100 keV.
Neutron energy spread 100 keV due to target thickness
and reaction kinematics caused by subtended solid angle
of the sample.
Cylinder of natural nickel, 5-cm high by 2.5-cm
diameter.

Total cross sections were deduced from the 125 deg
gamma-ray production cross sections. In the
conversion of 125-deg gamma-ray production cross
sections, dsigma/dOmega (125 deg) , to total gamma
ray production cross sections preparatory to the
inference of neutron excitation functions, an
integral of the gamma radiation over all angles must
be taken. The result can be expressed as sigmaT =
4*pi*(dsigma/dOmega 125 deg) M. The factor M takes
into account the fourth-order Legendre polynomial's
effect on the 125-deg cross section. (The
second-order Legendre polynomial is zero at this
angle.)

Values presented here as natural cross sections
include all the inferred neutron inelastic cross
sections of significance in all nickel isotopes with
the exception of that from the 1.19% abundant 61Ni
component.
